<br>
<br>
<br>
Light Amplification by Stimulated Emmision of Radiation.<br>
<br>
Lasers are becoming increasingly more powerful with every passing year as scientists experiment with new gases and solids. <br>
<br>
Lasers show up in an amazing range of products and technologies. You will find them in everything from CD players to dental drills to high-speed metal cutting machines to measuring systems. They all use lasers. But what is a laser? And what makes a laser beam different from the beam of a flashlight? <br>
<br>
How Lasers Work!<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.howstuffworks.com/laser.htm">www.howstuffworks.com/laser.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://static.howstuffworks.com/gif/laser-intro.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
A laser is a device that controls the way that energized atoms release photons. In a laser, very intense flashes of light or electrical discharges pump the lasing medium and create a large collection of excited-state atoms (atoms with higher-energy electrons). It is necessary to have a large collection of atoms in the excited state for the laser to work efficiently. <br>
<br>
Just as an electron absorbed some amount of energy to reach this excited level, it can also release this energy. The electron can simply relax, and in turn rid itself of some energy. This emitted energy comes in the form of photons (light energy). <br>
The light released is monochromatic, coherent and very directional. Laser light has a very tight beam and is very strong and concentrated. <br>
<br>
This does not occur in your ordinary flashlight -- in a flashlight, all of the atoms release their photons randomly. In stimulated emission, photon emission is organized. <br>
<br>
The other key to a laser is a pair of mirrors, one at each end of the lasing medium. Photons, with a very specific wavelength and phase, reflect off the mirrors to travel back and forth through the lasing medium. In the process, they stimulate other electrons to make the downward energy jump and can cause the emission of more photons of the same wavelength and phase. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://static.howstuffworks.com/gif/laser9.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
A cascade effect occurs, and soon we have propagated many, many photons of the same wavelength and phase. The mirror at one end of the laser is &quot;half-silvered,&quot; meaning it reflects some light and lets some light through. The light that makes it through is the laser light. <br>
<br>
Whether we use light or electricity to generate a laser the energy has to come from somewhere and in large amounts too. Nuclear reactors are an ideal method of delivering a complete and compact super laser.<br>
<br>
What use is a giant laser?<br>
<br>
Interplanetary Communications.<br>
<br>
A high intensity beam of coded light could reach Earth from anywhere within the solar system. Even interstellar transmissions are believed possible. Unlike radio transmissions which disperse more readily and would require far more power. A nuclear reactor combined with a powerful laser would allow clear communications over millions of kilometres.<br>
This is best compared to the light signals used to send coded messages between ships at sea. The equipment used to generate the coded flashes of light is more sophisticated, and the flashes of light are much more brief (billionths versus fractions of a second). However, the basic concept is not all that different from the communication technique employed by mariners for generations. <br>
<br>
SETI is even looking into the possibility that Alien civilisations might be using such methods to stay in contact.<br>
<br>
CNN: Telescope with eye only for aliens.<br>
&quot;The 1.8 metre Optical SETI Telescope now being built in Harvard, Massachusetts, will look for messages from the stars written in pulses of laser light.&quot;<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.cnn.com/2001/TECH/space/01/22/telescope.alien/">www.cnn.com/2001/TECH/space/01/22/telescope.alien/</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Defense.<br>
<br>
Lasers could also be used to detect rogue asteroids. Scouring the skies with high intensity beams and detecting the tell tale reflections in the same manner as radar but with far superior range. Using modern computers we can already bounce lasers of meteorites which exist only a moment before burning up.<br>
<br>
Naturally the bigger and more powerful the laser then the further it's range and the greater the warning time. Using nuclear power we could easily set up such early warning systems on every colonised World.<br>
<br>
Then ofcourse there is the military aspect. <br>
<br>
Laser gun zaps missile.<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/sci/tech/newsid_782000/782696.stm">news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/sci/tech/newsid_782000/782696.stm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
What space force wouldn't want a massive laser gun? In space the effective range would be dependant on how finely made the weapon is. Perhaps many thousands of kilometres. Even hundreds of thousands of kilometres. Also, nothing travels faster than light at 300,000 km per second.<br>
<br>
